postcontent:
For sale is a used Beretta PX4 Storm 

This is a rare and unique model as opposed to more common models of the PX4 Storm. This is a Type C which uses Beretta's constant action and has no external safety.

This model is extremely accurate but is not designed for the common conception of "accuracy"; that being, punching holes in paper at the range. This model is designed for true self defense. The trigger pull is designed to prevent the shooter from putting holes in things that he or she doesn't want holes in. 

The half cocked closed hammer allows for proper evaluation of a target, with action that is not as short as single but not as long as double. 

This gun also utilizes Beretta's rotating barrel system which greatly reduces recoil. For a 40, the snap is very minimal.

The PX4 Storm was designed to replaced the current military side arm and was the only pistol to pass all the tests to do so; unfortunately Uncle Sam decided not to spend the money.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Korea Era IR M3 Sniper scope
location: NW Suburbs, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
For sale and maybe partial trade is my Korea Era Us military Sniper Scope. Known officially as: M3, sniperscope, infrared, set no. 1, 20,000 volts. Made by american optical co. Buffalo, NY 6-23-51. Made to be mounted on a special M1 carbine known as the M2 carbine making the whole setup a M3. 

Very good condition. Really nice for how old it is. How does it compare to others? I don't know. I've never seen one that wasn't in a book or on the internet. This is the only one I have ever seen. Very rare, very cool piece of American Military History.

What is there and what isn't. This comes with the IR scope, IR Light, Foregrip/ Handle with the trigger, power transformer box, all necessary original wiring, 1 tube, original rubberized backpack (nice), and original chest. As far as what is missing? I'm really no expert but I think there was a tool set and more tubes. These are not there. And of course no .30 carbine. No rust anywhere and looks to be the original finish. Some scratches on the scope but not bad. A little corrosion on a small copper piece behind the light source. And it looks like the red filter is a little rough. The outside plastic of the light source is fine, its the red filter inside. I have not taken this apart or tried to clean any of it. 

Because this is so rare I did not want auction it, I wanted a lot of people to have a shot at owning it. Same with gun broker. I found it in Mn I would like a collector in MN to give it a good home. So I figured the only fair way to do it would be to take offers. So, if you want it, take a shot at it and email me your best offer. If you know what it is, you know what its worth, and how often you can find one.

As far as trades go... I might, might, take one of the following as partial trade with cash. 1. Ruger .44 carbine semi-auto. Prefer older tube fed. 2. Ruger No. 1 in 270 win, 280 rem, 30.06 or 303 brit. 3. HK usp Tactical all black. Of course these guns must be nice.

Of course all cash is always nice. FTF meet. Leave your name and number or I will not get back to you.

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  .308 winchester / 7.62x51 2 boxes/40rds
postcontent:
Selling off the boxes I have at $20 each, I will be at the Fremont Gun Show at Christensen Field tomorrow and will have this with me and out on my table. 


                                                                                                                                                  It is fmj and it is 150 grain, so it is usually great for old military rifles that were designed with twist rates for 147 - 155 grain ammo, but should also shoot well in modern .308 guns with faster twist rates for the 180-220 grain stuff. My FAL was designed for 147 gr and my Ishapore 2A1 was designed for 144gr, both shot terrible and wouldn't stabilize with any 168gr or heavier, the Ishy would even keyhole with some of the 155gr stuff, but they both shot great with this 150gr stuff. Should shoot ok in the later M1As and such that were designed for 168gr. If you've got an older rifle in .308, and it just doesnt seem to shoot right with the heavier hunting type ammo, then this is probably the stuff you need. 

                                                                                                                                            Also willing to trade for .22lr (depending on what it is and its age), most any .17 HMR, some other centerfire ammo, or for reloading supplies/equipment, especially bullets in certain cals, IMR4064, WIN231/HP38, and any primers.

title: For Sale:  Korea Era IR M3 Sniper scope
location: NW suburbs, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
For sale and maybe partial trade is my Korea Era Us military Sniper Scope. Known officially as: M3, sniperscope, infrared, set no. 1, 20,000 volts. Made by american optical co. Buffalo, NY 6-23-51. Made to be mounted on a special M1 carbine known as the M2 carbine making the whole setup a M3. 

Very good condition. Really nice for how old it is. How does it compare to others? I don't know. I've never seen one that wasn't in a book or on the internet. This is the only one I have ever seen. Very rare, very cool piece of American Military History.

What is there and what isn't. This comes with the IR scope, IR Light, Foregrip/ Handle with the trigger, power transformer box, all necessary original wiring, 1 tube, original rubberized backpack(nice), and original chest. As far as what is missing? I'm really no expert but I think there was a tool set and more tubes. These are not there. And of course no .30 carbine. No rust anywhere and looks to be the original finish. Some scratches on the scope but not bad. A little corrosion on a small copper piece behind the light source. And it looks like the red filter is a little rough. The outside plastic of the light source is fine, its the red filter inside. I have not taken this apart or tried to clean any of it. 

Because this is so rare I did not want auction it, I wanted a lot of people to have a shot at owning it. Same with gun broker. I found it in Mn I would like a collector in MN to give it a good home. So I figured the only fair way to do it wold be to take offers. So, if you want it, take a shot at it and email me your best offer. If you know what it is, you know what its worth, and how often you can find one.

As far as trades go... I might, might, take one of the following as partial trade with cash. 1. Ruger .44 carbine semi-auto. Prefer older tube fed. 2. Ruger No. 1 in 270 win, 280 rem, 30.06 or 303 brit. 3. HK usp Tactical all black. Of course these guns must be nice.

Of course all cash is always nice. FTF meet. Leave your name and number or I will not get back to you.

Thanks for looking.
